    <!-- No 1 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2008A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez la dérivée directionnelle de <m>f(x,y,z) = e^{xyz}</m> dans la direction <m>\llt 0,1,1\rgt</m>
      au point <m>(0,1,1)</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      <m>0</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      The partial derivatives, at a general point <m>(x,y,z)</m> and
      also at the point of interest <m>(0,1,1)</m>, are
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f_x(x,y,z)&amp;=yz e^{xyz}\qquad &amp;
         f_x(0,1,1)&amp;= 1
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y(x,y,z)&amp;=xz e^{xyz}\qquad &amp;
         f_x(0,1,1)&amp;= 0
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_z(x,y,z)&amp;=xy e^{xyz}\qquad &amp;
         f_z(0,1,1)&amp;= 0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      So <m>\vnabla f(0,1,1) =\llt 1,0,0\rgt</m> and the specified directional derivative
      is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vD_{\frac{\llt 0,1,1\rgt}{\sqrt{2}}}
      =\llt 1,0,0\rgt\cdot\frac{\llt 0,1,1\rgt}{\sqrt{2}}
      =0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 2 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2008A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez <m>\vnabla\big(y^2 + \sin(xy)\big)</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      <m>y\cos(xy)\,\vi +  [2y + x\cos(xy)]\,\vj</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      In two dimensions, write <m>g(x,y) = y^2+\sin(xy)</m>. Then
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla g =\llt g_x\,,\,g_y\rgt
                =\llt y\cos(xy)\,,\, 2y + x\cos(xy) \rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      In three dimensions, write <m>g(x,y,z) = y^2+\sin(xy)</m>. Then
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla g =\llt g_x\,,\,g_y\,,\,g_z\rgt
                =\llt y\cos(xy)\,,\, 2y + x\cos(xy)\,,\, 0 \rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 3 -->
    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez le taux de variation de la fonction donnée au point donné dans la direction donnée.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y)=3x-4y</m> au point <m>(0,2)</m> dans la direction <m>-2\vi</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y,z)=x^{-1}+y^{-1}+z^{-1}</m> à <m>(2,-3,4)</m> dans la direction
      <m>\vi+\vj+\vk</m>.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>-3</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>-\frac{61}{144\sqrt{3}}\approx-0.2446</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)
      The gradient of <m>f</m> is <m>\vnabla f(x,y)=\llt 3,-4\rgt</m>. So the specified rate of change is
      <me>
      \llt 3,-4\rgt\cdot\frac{\llt -2,0\rgt}{|\llt -2,0\rgt|}=-3
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>(b)
      The gradient of <m>f</m> is
        <m>\vnabla f(x,y,z)=\llt -x^{-2},-y^{-2},-z^{-2}\rgt</m>. In particular,
      the gradient of <m>f</m> at the point <m>(2,-3,4)</m> is
      <m>\vnabla f(2,-3,4)=\llt -\frac{1}{4},-\frac{1}{9},-\frac{1}{16}\rgt</m>.
      So the specified rate of change is
      <me>
      \llt -\frac{1}{4},-\frac{1}{9},-\frac{1}{16}\rgt\cdot
              \frac{\llt 1,1,1\rgt}{\sqrt{3}}=
              -\frac{61}{144\sqrt{3}}\approx-0.2446
      </me>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 5 -->
    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez <m>\vnabla f(a,b)</m> étant données les dérivées directionnelles
      <me>
      \vD_{(\vi+\vj)/\sqrt{2}}f(a,b)=3\sqrt{2}\qquad
      \vD_{(3\vi-4\vj)/5}f(a,b)=5
      </me>
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      Dénotez <m>\vnabla f(a,b)=\llt \a,\b\rgt</m>.
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      <m>\vnabla f(a,b)=\llt 7,-1\rgt</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
       Denote <m>\vnabla f(a,b)=\llt \a,\b\rgt</m>. We are told that
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      \llt\a,\b\rgt\cdot\llt\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\rgt&amp;=3\sqrt{2} &amp;
      &amp;\quad\text{or}\quad &amp;
      \a+\b&amp;=6
      </mrow><mrow>
      \llt\a,\b\rgt\cdot\llt\frac{3}{5},-\frac{4}{5}\rgt&amp;=5 &amp;
      &amp;\quad\text{or}\quad &amp;
      3\a-4\b&amp;=25
      </mrow>
      </md>
      Adding 4 times the first equation to the second equation gives <m>7\a=49</m>.
      Substituting <m>\a=7</m> into the first equation gives <m>\b=-1</m>. So
      <m>\vnabla f(a,b)=\llt 7,-1\rgt</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 7 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2006A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Assumez que la dérivée directionnelle de <m>w = f(x,y,z)</m> au point <m>P</m>
      est maximale dans la direction du vecteur <m>2\vi - \vj + \vk</m>, et
      que la la valeur de la dérivéee directionnelle dans cette direction est <m>3\sqrt{6}</m>.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Trouvez le vecteur gradient de <m>w = f(x,y,z)</m> en <m>P</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      Trouvez la dérivée directionnelle de <m>w = f(x,y,z)</m> en <m>P</m> dans la direction du vecteur <m>\vi + \vj</m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>6\vi - 3\vj + 3\vk</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)  Use <m>\vnabla f(P)</m> to denote the gradient vector of <m>f</m>
      at <m>P</m>. We are told that
      <ul>
      <li>
      directional derivative  of <m>f</m> at <m>P</m> is a maximum in the direction
      <m>2\vi - \vj + \vk</m>, which implies that <m>\vnabla f(P)</m> is parallel
      to <m>2\vi - \vj + \vk</m>, and
      </li>
      <li>
      the magnitude of the directional derivative in that direction is <m>3\sqrt{6}</m>,
      which implies that <m>|\vnabla f(P)|=3\sqrt{6}</m>.
      </li>
      </ul>
      So
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla f(P) = 3\sqrt{6} \frac{2\vi - \vj + \vk}{|2\vi - \vj + \vk|}
                   = 6\vi - 3\vj + 3\vk
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(b) The directional derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>P</m> in the direction <m>\vi+\vj</m> is
      <me>
      \vnabla f(P) \cdot\frac{\vi+\vj}{|\vi+\vj|}
      =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\big(6\vi - 3\vj + 3\vk\big)\cdot\big(\vi+\vj\big)
      =\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}}
      </me>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- Ceux ci sont ceux de "tangentes et normales"
    -->
    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Est-ce raisonnable de dire que les surfaces <m>x^2+y^2+(z-1)^2=1</m> et
      <m>x^2+y^2+(z+1)^2=1</m> sont tangentes l'une par rapport à l'autre en <m>(0,0,0)</m>?
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      Quels sont les plans tangents aux deux surfaces en <m>(0,0,0)</m>?
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      Oui. Le plan <m>z=0</m> est le plan tangent aux deux surfaces en <m>(0,0,0)</m>.
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      Write <m>F(x,y,z) = x^2+y^2+(z-1)^2-1</m> and <m>G(x,y,z) = x^2+y^2+(z+1)^2-1</m>.
      Let <m>S_1</m> denote the surface <m>F(x,y,z)=0</m> and <m>S_2</m> denote the surface
      <m>G(x,y,z)=0</m>.
      First note that <m>F(0,0,0)=G(0,0,0)=0</m> so that the point <m>(0,0,0)</m> lies
      on both <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m>. The gradients of <m>F</m> and <m>G</m> are
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla F(x,y,z)
        &amp;=\llt\pdiff{F}{x}(x,y,z)\,,\,
              \pdiff{F}{y}(x,y,z)\,,\,
              \pdiff{F}{z}(x,y,z)\rgt
      </mrow><mrow>
          &amp;=\llt 2x\,,\,2y\,,\,2(z-1)\rgt
      </mrow><mrow>
      \vnabla G(x,y,z)
        &amp;=\llt\pdiff{G}{x}(x,y,z)\,,\,
              \pdiff{G}{y}(x,y,z)\,,\,
              \pdiff{G}{z}(x,y,z)\rgt
      </mrow><mrow>
          &amp;=\llt 2x\,,\,2y\,,\,2(z+1)\rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      In particular,
      <me>
      \vnabla F(0,0,0)=\llt 0,0,-2\rgt\qquad
      \vnabla G(0,0,0)=\llt 0,0,2\rgt
      </me>
      so that the vector <m>\vk=-\frac{1}{2}\vnabla F(0,0,0)
                             =\frac{1}{2}\vnabla G(0,0,0)</m>
      is normal to both surfaces at <m>(0,0,0)</m>. So the tangent plane to
      both <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m> at <m>(0,0,0)</m> is
      <me>
      \vk\cdot\llt x-0,y-0,z-0\rgt=0\qquad\text{or}\qquad z=0
      </me>
      Denote by <m>P</m> the plane <m>z=0</m>.
      Thus <m>S_1</m> is tangent to <m>P</m> at <m>(0,0,0)</m> and <m>P</m> is tangent to <m>S_2</m>
      at <m>(0,0,0)</m>. So it is reasonable to say that <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m> are tangent at
      <m>(0,0,0)</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2009A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Soit <m>\displaystyle f(x,y)=\frac{x^2y}{x^4+2y^2}</m>.
      Trouvez le plan tangent à la surface <m>z = f(x,y)</m> au point
      <m>\left( -1\,,\,1\,,\,\frac{1}{3}\right)</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      <m>2x+y+9z=2</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
        <!--TODO
      We are going to use Theorem <xref ref="thm_tan_plane_f"/>.
      To do so-->We need the first order derivatives of <m>f(x,y)</m>
      at <m>(x,y)=(-1,1)</m>. So we find them first.
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f_x(x,y)&amp;=\frac{2xy}{x^4+2y^2}-\frac{x^2y(4x^3)}{{(x^4+2y^2)}^2}\qquad &amp;
      f_x(-1,1)&amp;=-\frac{2}{3} +\frac{4}{3^2}=-\frac{2}{9}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y(x,y)&amp;=\frac{x^2}{x^4+2y^2}-\frac{x^2y(4y)}{{(x^4+2y^2)}^2}\qquad &amp;
      f_y(-1,1)&amp;=\frac{1}{3} -\frac{4}{3^2}=-\frac{1}{9}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>The tangent plane is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      z&amp;=f(-1,1) + f_x(-1,1)\,(x+1) + f_y(-1,1)\,(y-1)
      </mrow><mrow>
       &amp; =\frac{1}{3} -\frac{2}{9}\,(x+1) -\frac{1}{9}\,(y-1)
      </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=\frac{2}{9}-\frac{2}{9}x-\frac{1}{9}y
      </mrow>
      </md>
      or <m>2x+y+9z=2</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2015D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez le plan tangent à
      <me>
      \frac{27}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2+3}}=9
      </me>
      au point <m>(2, 1, 1)</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      <m>2x+y+z = 6</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      The equation of the given surface is of the form <m>G(x,y,z)=9</m>
      with <m>G(x,y,z) =\frac{27}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2+3}}</m>. So,
      by Theorem <xref ref="thm_tan_plane_G"/>, a normal
      vector to the surface at <m>(2,1,1)</m> is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla G(2,1,1)
        &amp;=-\frac{1}{2}\ \frac{27}{(x^2+y^2+z^2+3)^{3/2}}\big(2x\,,\,2y\,,\,2z\big)
                                                \bigg|_{(x,y,z)=(2,1,1)}
      </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=-\llt 2\,,\,1\,,\,1\rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      and the equation of the tangent plane is
      <me>
      -\llt 2\,,\,1\,,\,1\rgt\cdot \llt x-2\,,\,y-1\,,\,z-1\rgt=0\qquad\text{or}\qquad
      2x+y+z = 6
      </me>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez les équations du plan tangent et de la droite normale aux graphes des fonctions spécifiées aux points spécifiés.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y)=x^2-y^2</m> en <m>(-2,1)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y)=e^{xy}</m> en <m>(2,0)</m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a)  Le plan tangent est  <m>4x+2y+z=-3</m>
            et la droite normale est  <m>\llt x,y,z\rgt=\llt -2,1,3\rgt+t\llt 4,2,1\rgt</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(b) Le plan tangent est  <m>2y-z=-1</m>
            et la droite normale est <m>\llt x,y,z\rgt=\llt 2,0,1\rgt+t\llt 0,2,-1\rgt</m>.
      </p>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)
      The specified graph is <m>z=f(x,y)=x^2-y^2</m> or <m>F(x,y,z)=x^2-y^2-z=0</m>.
      Observe that <m>f(-2,1)=3</m>. The vector
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla F(-2,1,3)
      &amp;= \llt F_x(x,y,z),F_y(x,y,z),F_z(x,y,z)\rgt\Big|_{(x,y,z)=(-2,1,3)}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \llt 2x,-2y,-1\rgt\Big|_{(x,y,z)=(-2,1,3)}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \llt -4,-2,-1\rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      is a normal vector to the graph at <m>(-2,1,3)</m>.
      So the tangent plane is
      <me>
      -4(x+2)-2(y-1)-(z-3)=0\text{ or } 4x+2y+z=-3
      </me>
      and the normal line is
      <me>
      \llt x,y,z\rgt=\llt -2,1,3\rgt+t\llt 4,2,1\rgt
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>(b)
      The specified graph is <m>z=f(x,y)=e^{xy}</m> or <m>F(x,y,z)=e^{xy}-z=0</m>.
      Observe that <m>f(2,0)=1</m>. The vector
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla F(2,0,1)
      &amp;= \llt F_x(x,y,z),F_y(x,y,z),F_z(x,y,z)\rgt\Big|_{(x,y,z)=(2,0,1)}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \llt ye^{xy},xe^{xy},-1\rgt\Big|_{(x,y,z)=(2,0,1)}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \llt 0,2,-1\rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      is a normal vector to the graph at <m>(2,0,1)</m>.
      So the tangent plane is
      <me>
      0(x-2)+2(y-0)-(z-1)=0\text{ or } 2y-z=-1
      </me>
      and the normal line is
      <me>
      \llt x,y,z\rgt=\llt 2,0,1\rgt+t\llt 0,2,-1\rgt
      </me>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2005D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Considérez la surface <m>z = f(x,y)</m> définie implicitement par l'équation
      <m>xyz^2 + y^2 z^3 = 3 + x^2</m>. Utilisez un vecteur gradient de dimension 3
      pour trouver l'équation du plan tangent à cette surface au point
      <m>(-1, 1, 2)</m>. Écrivez votre réponse sous la forme <m>z = ax + by + c</m>, où
      <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> et <m>c</m> sont constantes.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      <m>z = -\frac{3}{4} x- \frac{3}{2} y + \frac{11}{4}</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      We may use <m>G(x,y,z) = xyz^2 + y^2 z^3 - 3 - x^2 = 0</m> as an equation for
      the surface.  Note that <m>(-1,1,2)</m> really is on the surface since
      <md>
      <mrow>
      G(-1,1,2) = (-1)(1)(2)^2 + (1)^2 (2)^3 - 3 - (-1)^2
                = -4 + 8 - 3 - 1
                =0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      By Theorem <xref ref="thm_tan_plane_G"/>, since
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      G_x(x,y,z)&amp;=yz^2 -2x \qquad &amp;
          G_x(-1,1,2)&amp;=6
      </mrow><mrow>
      G_y(x,y,z)&amp;=xz^2 +2yz^3 \qquad &amp;
          G_y(-1,1,2)&amp;=12
      </mrow><mrow>
      G_z(x,y,z)&amp;=2xyz+3y^2z^2 \qquad &amp;
          G_z(-1,1,2)&amp;=8
      </mrow>
      </md>
      one normal vector to the surface at <m>(-1,1,2)</m> is
       <m>\vnabla G(-1,1,2) = \llt 6\,,\,12\,,\,8\rgt</m> and an equation
      of the tangent plane to the surface at <m>(-1,1,2)</m> is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \llt 6\,,\,12\,,\,8\rgt \cdot
           \llt x+1\,,\,y-1\,,\,z-2\rgt = 0\qquad\text{or}\qquad
      6x+12 y+ 8z = 22
      </mrow>
      </md>
      or
      <me>
      z = -\frac{3}{4} x- \frac{3}{2} y +\frac{11}{4}
      </me>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2008D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Une surface est donnée par
      <me>
      z = x^2 - 2xy + y^2 .
      </me>
      </p>

      <p><ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Trouvez l'équation du plan tangent à la surface en <m>x = a</m>, <m>y = 2a</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      Pour quelle(s) valeure(s) de <m>a</m> est-ce que le plan tangent est parallèle au plan
      <m>x - y + z = 1</m>?
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>2ax -2ay +z = -a^2</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>a=\frac{1}{2}</m>.
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)
      The surface is <m>G(x,y,z)=z-x^2+2xy-y^2=0</m>. When <m>x=a</m> and <m>y=2a</m>
       and <m>(x,y,z)</m> is on the surface, we have <m>z= a^2-2(a)(2a) +(2a)^2=a^2</m>.
      So, by Theorem <xref ref="thm_tan_plane_G"/>,
      a normal vector to this surface at <m>(a,2a,a^2)</m> is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \vnabla G(a,2a,a^2) = \llt -2x+2y\,,\,2x-2y\,,\,1\rgt\Big|_{(x,y,z)=(a,2a,a^2)}
                          = \llt 2a\,,\,-2a\,,\,1\rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      and the equation of the tangent plane is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \llt 2a\,,\,-2a\,,\,1\rgt\cdot\llt x-a\,,\,y-2a\,,\,z-a^2\rgt =0
      \quad\text{or}\quad
      2ax -2ay +z = -a^2
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(b) The two planes are parallel when their two normal vectors,
      namely <m>\llt 2a\,,\,-2a\,,\,1\rgt</m> and <m>\llt 1\,,\,-1\,,\,1\rgt</m>,
      are parallel. This is the case if and only if <m>a=\frac{1}{2}</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2010D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez le plan tangent et la droite normale à la surface
      <m>z=f(x,y)=\frac{2y}{x^2+y^2}</m> en <m>(x,y)=(-1,2)</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      Le plan tangent est <m>\frac{8}{25}x-\frac{6}{25}y-z=-\frac{8}{5}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        La droite normale est
         <m>\llt x,y,z\rgt = \llt -1,2,\frac{4}{5}\rgt
                        +t \llt \frac{8}{25}\,,\,-\frac{6}{25}\,,\,-1\rgt</m>.
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      The first order partial derivatives of <m>f</m> are
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f_x(x,y) &amp; = -\frac{4xy}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}\quad &amp;
            f_x(-1,2) &amp; = \frac{8}{25}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y(x,y) &amp; = \frac{2}{x^2+y^2}-\frac{4y^2}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}\quad &amp;
            f_y(-1,2) &amp; = \frac{2}{5}-\frac{16}{25}
                        =-\frac{6}{25}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      <!--TODO So, by Theorem <xref ref="thm_tan_plane_f"/>,
      --> normal vector to the surface at <m>(x,y)=(-1,2)</m> is
      <m>\llt \frac{8}{25}\,,\,-\frac{6}{25}\,,\,-1\rgt</m>.
      As <m>f(-1,2)= \frac{4}{5}</m>, the tangent plane is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      &amp;\llt \frac{8}{25}\,,\,-\frac{6}{25}\,,\,-1\rgt\cdot\llt x+1\,,\,y-2\,,\,
               z -\frac{4}{5}\rgt=0
      </mrow><mrow>
       &amp; \quad \text{or}\quad
      \frac{8}{25}x-\frac{6}{25}y-z=-\frac{8}{5}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      and the normal line is
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \llt x,y,z\rgt = \llt -1,2,\frac{4}{5}\rgt
                        +t \llt \frac{8}{25}\,,\,-\frac{6}{25}\,,\,-1\rgt
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>
    
